ts (likely)\n    *   Flyway (database migrations)\n    *   Docker\n*   **Frontend:**\n    *   Vue.js\n    *   Vue Router\n    *   Vuex\n    *   JavaScript/TypeScript (likely)\n    *   Webpack/Vite\n*   **Database:**\n    *   (Likely) PostgreSQL, MySQL, or similar relational database.  The `application.properties` or `application.yml` file in the backend will contain the database connection details.\n\n**How the Application Works (Inferred):**\n\n1.  **User Interaction:** Users interact with the frontend (Vue.js application) in their web browser.\n2.  **API Requests:** The frontend makes HTTP requests to the backend API (Spring Boot application) to perform actions like creating retrospectives, adding cards, voting, etc.\n3.  **Authentication:** The backend authenticates and authorizes users before processing their requests.\n4.  **Business Logic:** The backend's services handle the business logic, validating data, applying rules, and interacting with the database.\n5.  **Data Persistence:** The backend's repositories use Spring Data JPA to interact with the database, storing and retrieving data.\n6.  **Real-time Updates:**  WebSockets (likely) are used to push real-time updates from the backend to the frontend, ensuring that all users see the latest changes to the retrospective board.\n7.  **Database Updates:**  Database updates are performed using Flyway migration scripts to keep the database schema up-to-date.\n8.  **Deployment:** The application is deployed as a set of Docker containers, making it easy to deploy to various environments.\n\n**Further Investigation:**\n\nTo get a more in-depth understanding, I would recommend the following:\n\n*   Examine the `application.properties` or `application.yml` files in the backend to see the database configuration.\n*   Look at the Vuex store (`frontend/src/store/`) to understand how the frontend manages its state.\n*   Investigate the WebSocket implementation in the backend to understand how real-time updates are handled